% ==========================================================================
\begin{abstract}
% ==========================================================================
Asthma exacerbations are acute episodes of worsening respiratory symptoms
that account for the majority of preventable morbidity, hospital use, and
cost in chronic asthma care.  Continuous wearable and digital-health
signals offer the potential to anticipate these events early enough to
trigger structured self-management.  This report covers the full arc of
our final-year work: an initial smartwatch-only day-level pipeline (the
\emph{progress-report} system), a set of methodological fixes prompted by
post-submission re-analysis, the addition of two further deep-learning
families (Tier-3, RNN and LSTM) and a multi-seed evaluation protocol, a
clinically reformulated prediction task that we call
\emph{Event-Episode Pre-Onset Anticipation}, and finally a
generalisation-stress-test that combines leave-one-patient-out
cross-validation with a patient-level permutation null.

The reformulated task isolates the question that clinicians actually
care about--given a patient's recent multimodal record, can we anticipate
the onset of a new exacerbation episode in the next few days?--and runs
the full pipeline (labels, samples, features, model selection, sensor
ablation, leakage probe, bootstrap confidence intervals) under
patient-disjoint splits at every stage.  Headline numbers on a held-out
4-patient test fold are high
(Random-Forest \rocauc{}~=~0.879; XGBoost on smartinhaler-only
features \rocauc{}~=~0.964; multi-seed RNN test \rocauc{}~=~0.65~$\pm$~0.26),
but leave-one-patient-out validation reveals that the strongest tabular
score collapses to pooled \rocauc{}~$=$~0.354 across the cohort and that
a patient-level permutation null cannot distinguish the headline
performance from chance ($p$~=~0.40 for the headline Random Forest,
$p$~=~0.22 for the inhaler-only XGBoost).  We report these findings
together because they are the honest answer that an $n$~=~18 cohort can
support: discriminative power is real on a favourable split, but
cross-patient generalisation at clinically useful effect sizes has not
been established.  We discuss the implications for deployment and the
methodological lessons for similar wearable-cohort studies.
\end{abstract}

\tableofcontents
\newpage

% ==========================================================================
\section{Introduction}\label{sec:intro}
% ==========================================================================

Asthma is a chronic inflammatory airway disease that affects an estimated
262~million people worldwide and contributes to approximately
455{,}000~deaths annually~\cite{who2024}.  Exacerbations -- acute or
sub-acute episodes of worsening symptoms or lung-function decline -- are
the most consequential events in asthma care.  They lead to emergency
visits, hospitalisation, and life-threatening deterioration when not
recognised early~\cite{bourdin2019}, and the total annual cost of asthma
in the United States alone is estimated at \$81.9~billion~\cite{nurmagambetov2018}.

Two complementary lines of evidence motivate the present work.  First,
clinical outcomes improve when worsening is identified early and patients
act on structured self-management plans~\cite{pinnock2015}.  Second, a
recent systematic review~\cite{cokorudy2024} supports the feasibility of
detecting exacerbation-related changes via continuous digital markers
derived from wearable and mobile-health sensors.  Smartwatches in
particular -- now capturing minute-level heart rate, activity type, step
count, and intensity in everyday environments -- are a practical
deployment platform for such monitoring~\cite{taylor2020}.

We formulate early warning as a supervised time-series prediction task:
given a recent multimodal record, estimate the probability that an
exacerbation occurs within a defined upcoming horizon.  Using the
publicly available AAMOS-00 dataset~\cite{tsang2023}, we develop an
end-to-end pipeline spanning data cleaning, label construction, feature
engineering, tabular baselines, deep-learning sequence models, and -- in
this final phase -- a generalisation stress-test designed to reveal
whether reported scores reflect genuine signal or split-specific
artefacts.

\subsection{Contributions in this Final Report}

This report extends the progress-report system in five concrete ways:

\begin{enumerate}[nosep]
  \item \textbf{Methodological audit.}  We retrospectively identify three
        weaknesses in the progress-report pipeline -- 1-hour-stride
        overlapping windows, a week-level positive label that propagates
        identical targets to ${\sim}168$~adjacent samples, and a 16.5\%/48.2\%
        prevalence mismatch between train and test caused by a small,
        single-seed patient split -- and show how each is addressed in the
        reformulated pipeline (Section~\ref{sec:fixes}).
  \item \textbf{Tier-3 deep-learning models.}  We add a vanilla RNN and an
        LSTM to the GRU/CNN pair from the progress report and re-train all
        four families under a unified multi-seed protocol
        (Section~\ref{sec:tier3}).
  \item \textbf{Reformulated task: Event-Episode Pre-Onset Anticipation.}
        We replace the week-level binary label with a per-episode label
        defined over an $L$-day window ending the day \emph{before} each
        clinical onset, swept over three thresholds, three lookbacks, and
        three washouts (27~cells), with patient-disjoint splits at every
        stage (Section~\ref{sec:onset}).
  \item \textbf{Sensor ablation and a label-leakage probe.}  We refit each
        cell-winner on nine sensor subsets (729~refits) and run a 5-shuffle
        label-permutation probe across all 81~configurations to bound the
        ceiling under truly random labels (Section~\ref{sec:onset-results}).
  \item \textbf{Generalisation stress-test.}  We re-evaluate the two
        headline tabular configurations under
        leave-one-patient-out cross-validation across all 18~patients and
        run a 200-permutation patient-level null
        (Section~\ref{sec:lopo}).  We report the honest conclusions even
        when they contradict the headline numbers.
\end{enumerate}

% ==========================================================================
\section{Literature Review}\label{sec:lit}
% ==========================================================================

\subsection{Machine learning for asthma exacerbation prediction}

A narrative review by Molfino and Turcatel~\cite{molfino2024} maps the
machine-learning literature on asthma exacerbation prediction, spanning
logistic regression, tree-based methods, and deep learning.  Key
practical challenges identified across studies include heterogeneous
outcome definitions, limited external validation, and inconsistent
generalisability across patient populations.

\subsection{Home-monitoring time series and the false-alarm problem}

De~Hond et~al.~\cite{dehond2022} compared classical and machine-learning
models for predicting severe exacerbations from home-monitoring time
series and found that machine learning did not outperform logistic
regression in their setting.  They explicitly discuss the
\emph{false-alarm problem} inherent to rare-event prediction: even
models with high \rocauc{} may produce unacceptable false-positive rates
when the base rate of exacerbations is low.  Their findings motivate
reporting precision--recall curves and sensitivity at controlled
false-alarm rates -- a recommendation we adopt throughout.

\subsection{Connected inhalers and multimodal monitoring}

Lugogo et~al.~\cite{lugogo2022} demonstrated predictive performance using
connected-inhaler signals and gradient boosting, achieving clinically
meaningful discrimination from a single modality.  Tsang
et~al.~\cite{tsang2023} introduced AAMOS-00, the multimodal dataset on
which our work is built; it combines smartwatch sensing, smart-inhaler
data, peak-flow measurements, and weekly questionnaires.  The DIGIPREDICT
protocol~\cite{chan2024} further reflects the field's movement toward
multimodal, physiological early-warning systems.

\subsection{Digital markers and wearable data quality}

A 2024 systematic review by Cokorudy et~al.~\cite{cokorudy2024} catalogues
multiple digital markers associated with asthma exacerbations and
evaluates their potential for near real-time monitoring.  Cho
et~al.~\cite{cho2021} review wearable data quality challenges, including
missing segments and sensor noise, motivating robust preprocessing and
missingness-aware modeling.

\subsection{Gaps addressed}

Three gaps recur across the literature: (i) robust modeling under
rare-event conditions with appropriate calibration and false-alarm
control; (ii) effective learning from noisy, incomplete, heterogeneous
wearable time series; and (iii) principled fusion of multimodal streams.
The present report addresses (i) and (iii) directly and identifies (ii)
as the binding constraint for the AAMOS-00 cohort.

% ==========================================================================
\section{Dataset}\label{sec:data}
% ==========================================================================

\subsection{AAMOS-00 overview}

We use the AAMOS-00 dataset~\cite{tsang2023}, publicly available under the
CC~BY~4.0 licence~\cite{datashare}.  Phase~2 of the study enrolled
22~participants and provides ${\sim}2{,}054$~unique patient-days of data
spanning four modalities (smartwatch, smartinhaler, peak flow,
environment) plus a weekly clinical questionnaire and a small set of
patient-static descriptors.

After cleaning, 20~unique users contribute usable smartwatch data and
18~unique users contribute usable weekly questionnaire entries.  The
weekly questionnaire is the ground-truth source for exacerbation labels
in every formulation of the task; the 18~users with valid questionnaire
data form the cohort used throughout the rest of this report.

\subsection{Modality summary}

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{AAMOS-00 modality coverage used in the final report
($n$~=~18~users).}
\label{tab:modalities}
\small
\begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{lXrl}
\toprule
\textbf{Modality} & \textbf{Signals} & \textbf{Patient-days} &
\textbf{Used in} \\
\midrule
Smartwatch         & Heart rate, activity type, intensity, steps &
${\sim}1{,}567$ & All phases \\
Smartinhaler       & Rescue-inhaler actuation timestamps &
${\sim}694$    & Sec.~\ref{sec:onset} \\
Peak-flow meter    & AM/PM peak expiratory flow &
${\sim}1{,}099$ & Sec.~\ref{sec:onset} \\
Environment        & Weather / pollen / air quality &
Throughout       & Sec.~\ref{sec:onset} \\
Weekly questionnaire & 0--6 symptom scores; clinical event flags &
${\sim}1{,}583$ & Label source \\
Patient-static     & Age band, sex, severity tier &
$n=18$           & Merged feature \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabularx}
\end{table}

\subsection{Cleaning}

Smartwatch streams were de-duplicated per user; heart-rate values outside
the physiologically plausible range (${<}30$ or ${>}220$~bpm) were set to
missing; short gaps (${\leq}5$~min) were forward-filled and longer gaps
left as NaN.  After cleaning, the smartwatch corpus contains
$2{,}101{,}759$ minute-level rows with an overall HR-missingness rate of
$25.3\%$, driven mainly by periods when the device was charging or not
worn.  Per-user HR missingness ranges from $15.8\%$ to $61.6\%$,
reflecting real-world adherence heterogeneity.

% ==========================================================================
\section{Phase~I: Initial Day-Level Smartwatch Pipeline}\label{sec:phase1}
% ==========================================================================

The progress-report system, summarised here for completeness, frames
exacerbation prediction as a 24-hour-window classification problem driven
exclusively by smartwatch data.

\subsection{Window construction and features}

Each 24-hour history window ($1{,}440$~minutes of HR, activity type,
intensity, and step count) was advanced with a 1-hour stride and required
${\geq}70\%$ non-missing minutes for retention, yielding 31{,}125 windows
across 18~users.  Tabular models consumed 29~engineered features per
window covering HR statistics (mean, median, std, min, max, slope,
missingness), step features (sum, mean, max, slope), activity-state
fractions, and derived day/night summaries.

\subsection{Labels}

A week was labelled positive if a clinical event was recorded
(doctor visit, hospital/ER admission, oral-steroid course) \emph{or} if
${\geq}3$ of the six 0--6 symptom domains were simultaneously elevated
(${\geq}4$).  Every 24-hour window within a positive week inherited the
positive label, yielding a $30.3\%$ positive rate across all windows.

\subsection{Models and results}

Tier-1 baselines (logistic regression, random forest, XGBoost) used the
29 engineered features.  Tier-2 sequence models comprised a two-layer
GRU operating on $5\times$-subsampled sequences ($288\times 4$, 38{,}465
parameters) and a three-layer 1D~CNN on the full sequence
($1{,}440\times 4$, 23{,}969 parameters).  Headline numbers on the
single 25\%-patient-wise test split are reproduced in
Table~\ref{tab:phase1}.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Phase~I results on the single patient-wise test split
(sorted by \rocauc).}
\label{tab:phase1}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lccccccc}
\toprule
\textbf{Model} & \textbf{Acc} & \textbf{Prec} & \textbf{Rec} &
\textbf{F1} & \textbf{\rocauc} & \textbf{\prauc} & \textbf{Brier} \\
\midrule
GRU (2-layer)       & 0.483 & 0.481 & \textbf{0.918} & 0.632 & \textbf{0.717} & \textbf{0.773} & 0.225 \\
Ensemble (60\%~GRU) & 0.726 & 0.823 & 0.549 & \textbf{0.659} & 0.653 & 0.762 & \textbf{0.221} \\
Random Forest       & 0.678 & 0.854 & 0.402 & 0.547 & 0.633 & 0.724 & 0.254 \\
XGBoost             & 0.612 & 0.812 & 0.255 & 0.388 & 0.581 & 0.654 & 0.312 \\
Logistic Reg.\      & 0.543 & 0.523 & 0.588 & 0.554 & 0.578 & 0.658 & 0.313 \\
CNN (3-layer)       & 0.483 & 0.475 & 0.694 & 0.564 & 0.520 & 0.530 & 0.320 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\paragraph{\textcolor{red}{Warning -- do not cite these numbers as evidence of
model performance.}}
The numbers in Table~\ref{tab:phase1} are reported here only to document
the progress-report system as it was submitted.  They are \emph{not}
comparable to any later results in this report and should not be cited
as evidence that any of these models work.  The Phase~II audit
(Section~\ref{sec:fixes}) identifies the protocol-level reasons for
that caveat; the Phase~V cross-patient evaluation
(Section~\ref{sec:lopo}) shows that even the strongest configuration of
the reformulated pipeline does not produce statistically distinguishable
signal under a patient-level null.  Phase~I numbers should be read
strictly as a starting point for the methodological discussion.

A 5-fold GroupKFold cross-validation for the Random Forest reported
mean \rocauc{}~$=~0.611~\pm~0.226$ with a per-fold range of
$[0.37,\,0.91]$, providing the first quantitative signal that
inter-patient variance dominates this task.

% ==========================================================================
\section{Phase~II: Methodological Audit and Fixes}\label{sec:fixes}
% ==========================================================================

Post-submission re-analysis surfaced three weaknesses in the Phase~I
protocol.  None invalidate the qualitative finding that the GRU outranks
tabular baselines on this split, but each individually inflates the
reported numerical scores and motivates the redesign described in
Sections~\ref{sec:tier3}--\ref{sec:onset}.

\paragraph{Within-patient temporal redundancy.}
A 1-hour stride over a 24-hour window means adjacent windows share
${\sim}96\%$ of their data.  Although the patient-wise split prevents
cross-patient leakage, every patient's positive week contributes
${\sim}168$ near-duplicate positive windows.  This inflates effective
sample counts and gives any model that overfits to within-patient
idiosyncrasies (e.g.\ a particular user's resting-HR baseline) a large
reward at training time.

\paragraph{Coarse week-level label.}
A single binary label is propagated to all ${\sim}168$~windows in a week.
The model is therefore rewarded for distinguishing "patient was in a
positive week" rather than "patient is about to enter a positive
episode."  These are different tasks; the former is much easier and
much less clinically useful.

\paragraph{Train/test prevalence mismatch.}
The single $\texttt{GroupShuffleSplit}$ produces a $16.5\%$ positive rate
in train and a $48.2\%$ positive rate in test -- a 3$\times$ mismatch
that systematically inflates threshold-dependent metrics on the test
side.  This is an artefact of patient-wise splitting on a small cohort
where individual patients dominate the prevalence; it is not addressed
by class-weighting alone.

\paragraph{Single-seed deep-learning evaluation.}
Phase~I reported one training run per architecture.  Section~\ref{sec:tier3}
shows that the seed variance of the recurrent models on this cohort is
$\sigma~\approx~0.26$ in \rocauc{}, which means a single-seed headline is
not interpretable on its own.

The redesign in Sections~\ref{sec:tier3}--\ref{sec:onset} addresses each
of these issues: patient-disjoint splits become a hard constraint at
every stage (HPO, ablation, leakage probe, final test); positives are
defined per-episode and anchored on the day before each clinical onset,
removing within-patient label propagation; all deep-learning families
are run for 5~seeds; and a separate leave-one-patient-out and
patient-permutation protocol is added on top to test cross-cohort
generalisation.

% ==========================================================================
\section{Phase~III: Tier-3 Deep-Learning Models and Multi-Seed
Evaluation}\label{sec:tier3}
% ==========================================================================

Phase~II extends Phase~I's two deep-learning families (GRU, 1D~CNN) with
two further sequence-model families and adopts a 5-seed evaluation
protocol throughout.

\subsection{Added architectures}

\paragraph{Vanilla RNN.}
A two-layer Elman RNN with hidden dimension~64, $\tanh$ activation, and
dropout~0.2 between layers.  Included as a minimum-capacity recurrent
baseline so that the marginal benefit of gating in the GRU and LSTM is
identifiable.

\paragraph{LSTM.}
A two-layer LSTM with hidden dimension~64, dropout~0.2.  The additional
input/forget/output gating relative to the GRU is the standard
comparison point in the wearable-sequence literature.

All four families (RNN, LSTM, GRU, CNN) consume the same input tensor at
the reformulated task: an $L\times D$ daily-feature matrix
(Section~\ref{sec:onset}).  Optimisation uses Adam, BCE-with-logits with
a positive-class up-weight, batch size~64, early stopping on validation
loss with patience~5, and a maximum of 30~epochs.

\subsection{Multi-seed protocol}

For each architecture and the winning $(T,\,L,\,W)$ cell from Phase~III
HPO, training was repeated for 5~seeds
$\{42,\,43,\,44,\,45,\,46\}$ on the \emph{same} train/val/test patient
split.  The only sources of variation across seeds are weight
initialisation, mini-batch ordering, and dropout sampling.  Reporting
the mean, standard deviation, and range across seeds is necessary
because, as shown in Section~\ref{sec:tier3-results} below, the
seed-only variance dominates almost every other source of noise on this
cohort.

\subsection{Headline multi-seed result}\label{sec:tier3-results}

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{RNN multi-seed test \rocauc{} at the Phase-III winning cell
$(T=3,\,L=14,\,W=14)$ on the same 4-patient test fold.  Every cell uses
the \emph{identical} data, architecture, and hyperparameters; only the
random seed varies.}
\label{tab:rnn-multiseed}
\small
\begin{tabular}{rc}
\toprule
\textbf{Seed} & \textbf{Test \rocauc{}} \\
\midrule
42 & 0.900 \\
43 & 0.920 \\
44 & 0.387 \\
45 & 0.654 \\
46 & 0.381 \\
\midrule
Mean $\pm$ std & $0.648 \pm 0.263$ \\
Range          & $[0.381,\,0.920]$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The within-seed range of \emph{the same model on the same data}
($\Delta\rocauc=0.54$) exceeds the gap between any two model families
in Phase~I (Table~\ref{tab:phase1}).  Reporting a single-seed
\rocauc{}~$=$~0.902 (as Phase~I would have done) is therefore a draw
from a heavy-tailed distribution centred near chance; the corresponding
finding is that recurrent models on this cohort are not stably
identifiable and that any test number not accompanied by a seed
distribution is unsafe to interpret.  This observation drives the
generalisation analysis in Section~\ref{sec:lopo}.

% ==========================================================================
\section{Phase~IV: Event-Episode Pre-Onset Anticipation}\label{sec:onset}
% ==========================================================================

The reformulated task replaces the week-level label of Phase~I with a
per-episode label whose positives are anchored on the day before each
clinical onset.  We refer to this throughout as
\textbf{Event-Episode Pre-Onset Anticipation}.  The clinical question it
poses is: \emph{given a patient's recent multimodal record, is the
patient on the trajectory toward a new exacerbation episode in the next
few days?}

\subsection{Definitions}

Let the weekly worsening score~$w_t$ be the count of the six symptom
domains that exceed threshold~$T$ on a given week, plus a binary
contribution from the clinical event flag.  A week is an
\emph{event week} when $w_t\,{\geq}\,T$; a maximal run of event weeks is
an \emph{event episode} with \emph{onset day}~$E$ (the first day of the
first event week in the run).  The pre-onset window of episode $E$
under lookback~$L$ is the set of days $[E-L,\;E-1]$ -- explicitly
\emph{excluding} $E$ itself, because the goal is anticipation, not
detection.

A washout~$W$ specifies the number of days after an event-episode end
during which no negative sample may be drawn.  Negative samples are
per-day anchors $a$ in stable non-event weeks whose lookback window
$[a-L,\,a-1]$ does not overlap any positive week, event day,
event-episode span, or washout interval.

The grid swept in Phase~III is
$T\in\{2,3,4\}$, $L\in\{3,7,14\}$, $W\in\{0,7,14\}$ for 27~cells.

\subsection{Patient-disjoint three-way split}\label{sec:onset-split}

A single deterministic split is produced once from the 18 unique
\texttt{user\_key}s under \texttt{np.random.default\_rng(seed=42)} and
reused at every downstream stage:

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{The fixed 13~/~3~/~4 patient-disjoint split used throughout
Phase~III--Phase~IV.}
\label{tab:split}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lcl}
\toprule
\textbf{Fold} & \textbf{Size} & \textbf{User keys} \\
\midrule
Train & 13 & 939, 294, 113, 808, 343, 562, 917, 278, 328, 867, 190, 701, 454 \\
Val   &  3 & 625, 514, 398 \\
Test  &  4 & 764, 473, 702, 447 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

With four test patients and per-cell positive counts in the range
2--5, every test-side metric is downstream of those four patients'
behaviour.  This is what makes the headline \rocauc{} values in
Section~\ref{sec:onset-results} simultaneously precise (the model
genuinely ranks those test rows the way the table reports) and fragile
(swapping the test fold can move the headline by 0.3 or more, as
Section~\ref{sec:lopo} demonstrates).

\subsection{Sample population and class prevalence}\label{sec:onset-counts}

Across the 18~patients, the number of pre-onset positive samples is
bounded above by the number of distinct event episodes per patient,
which is small: at $L=14$ each of the three threshold settings produces
53--55 positive samples across the full cohort (the remaining 8--10
candidate positives are dropped because $E-L<0$, i.e.\ not enough
observation history before the patient's first episode).  Negative-side
pruning by the washout~$W$ and the various exclusion rules of
Section~\ref{sec:onset} removes a few hundred candidate days, but the
positive count is essentially the binding constraint on this task.
Table~\ref{tab:onset-counts} reports the counts at $L=14$, which
covers every $(T,\,L,\,W)$ that appears in any later table.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Sample counts at $L=14$, summed across all 18~patients.
``Positives'' is the number of pre-onset windows used as positive
samples after the $E-L\geq 0$ filter.  Test-side positive counts in
Sections~\ref{sec:onset-results}--\ref{sec:lopo} are a strict subset of
these counts restricted to the 4 test patients.}
\label{tab:onset-counts}
\small
\begin{tabular}{ccccccc}
\toprule
$T$ & $L$ & $W$ & \textbf{Positives} & \textbf{Negatives} &
\textbf{Total} & \textbf{Positive rate} \\
\midrule
2 & 14 & 0  & 54 & 1191 & 1245 & 4.34\% \\
2 & 14 & 7  & 54 & 1130 & 1184 & 4.56\% \\
2 & 14 & 14 & 54 & 1067 & 1121 & 4.82\% \\
3 & 14 & 0  & 53 & 1191 & 1244 & 4.26\% \\
3 & 14 & 7  & 53 & 1134 & 1187 & 4.47\% \\
3 & 14 & 14 & 53 & 1071 & 1124 & 4.72\% \\
4 & 14 & 0  & 55 & 1191 & 1246 & 4.41\% \\
4 & 14 & 7  & 55 & 1139 & 1194 & 4.61\% \\
4 & 14 & 14 & 55 & 1076 & 1131 & 4.86\% \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

At the headline RF cell $(T=4,\,L=14,\,W=7)$, the four test patients
contribute only \textbf{4 positives out of 339~test samples} (positive
rate $1.18\%$); at the headline XGB-inhaler cell $(T=4,\,L=14,\,W=14)$,
4 positives out of 325 (1.23\%).  This is the binding statistical fact
behind every reported test number.  An \rocauc{} score on 4~test
positives is the average of $4\times(N-4)\sim 1280$ pairwise
positive--vs--negative comparisons, and a single mis-ranked positive
flips ${\sim}300$ of those pairs; the Phase-V evaluation
(Section~\ref{sec:lopo}) is the protocol-level fix for this.

\subsection{Feature pipeline}

For each sample row with anchor day~$a$ we aggregate the per-day
feature tables of each requested sensor source over the lookback window
$[a-L,\,a-1]$ using mean / std / min / max / slope / last-value / count
summaries, then merge the patient-static descriptors.  The full
all-sensor feature dimension is $\sim 72$~at $L=14$; with sensor
ablation it drops accordingly.  The deep-learning models consume the
underlying $L\times D$ daily matrix directly (no within-window
summarisation).

\subsection{HPO and model selection}\label{sec:onset-hpo}

We run HPO over LR (8~grids), RF (24~grids), and XGB (32~grids) per
cell, scoring on validation \prauc{}, and select one winner per
(cell, algorithm) triple.  The deep-learning HPO selects best
architecture per cell from \{GRU, LSTM, RNN, CNN\} also on validation
\prauc{}.  Test rows remain untouched.

Table~\ref{tab:hpo-winners} reports the winning hyperparameters for the
four cells that feed every later result table.  Validation \prauc{}
values are uniformly low (best $0.25$ at $L=14$); this is the
expected behaviour given the $\sim 4\%$ class prevalence in
Table~\ref{tab:onset-counts} and the 3-patient validation fold of
Table~\ref{tab:split}, and it implies that the HPO winners are
selected on a very small number of validation positives (1--4 across
these cells), which is itself a source of variance.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Phase~IV HPO winners that feed every later result table.
Validation \prauc{} is the model-selection criterion; test columns are
shown for reference but are not used to choose winners.}
\label{tab:hpo-winners}
\scriptsize
\begin{tabular}{lcccll cc}
\toprule
\textbf{Algo} & $T$ & $L$ & $W$ & \textbf{Sensor subset} &
\textbf{Winning hyperparameters} & \textbf{Val \prauc{}} &
\textbf{Test \rocauc{}} \\
\midrule
RF  & 4 & 14 & 7  & all (4 modalities)  & cw=balanced; $n$=200; depth=None; leaf=1 & 0.250 & 0.879 \\
RF  & 4 & 14 & 14 & all                 & cw=balanced; $n$=500; depth=6; leaf=1    & 0.015 & 0.650 \\
XGB & 4 & 14 & 0  & all                 & $n$=200; depth=6; lr=0.05; subs=0.7      & 0.034 & 0.759 \\
XGB & 4 & 14 & 14 & smartinhaler only   & $n$=200; depth=3; lr=0.1; subs=1.0       & 0.013 & 0.964 \\
RNN & 3 & 14 & 14 & all (daily tensor)  & hidden=64; layers=2; dropout=0.2         & 0.123 & $0.648 \pm 0.263$\textsuperscript{$\dagger$} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\noindent\textsuperscript{$\dagger$}\,5-seed mean $\pm$ std,
Table~\ref{tab:rnn-multiseed}.  Hyperparameters: \texttt{cw}~=
class weight, \texttt{$n$}~= number of estimators / trees,
\texttt{depth}~= maximum tree depth, \texttt{leaf}~= minimum samples
per leaf, \texttt{lr}~= learning rate, \texttt{subs}~= row-subsample
ratio.

\subsection{Sensor ablation and label-leakage probe}\label{sec:onset-ablation}

Each cell-winner is refit on nine sensor subsets (all, four singletons,
four leave-one-out) with hyperparameters \emph{locked} from HPO,
yielding $9\times 27\times 3=729$ refits.  Separately, a 5-shuffle
label-permutation probe across all 81~configurations bounds the ceiling
under truly random labels; the pooled mean validation \rocauc{} under
permuted labels is $0.5046$~(95\% empirical interval $\approx
[0.25,\,0.75]$), consistent with no leakage.

\subsection{Final test evaluation with bootstrap CIs}\label{sec:onset-results}

The Phase-III winners are refit on train$\cup$val and evaluated once on
the four-patient test fold.  Bootstrap 95\% confidence intervals are
computed from 2000 resamples of the test predictions; F1-relevant
thresholds are tuned via a train-only refit
($\tau^{\star}$ in Table~\ref{tab:onset-headline}).

\paragraph{\textcolor{red}{Read this before the headline table.}}
The numbers in Table~\ref{tab:onset-headline} are computed on a single
4-patient test fold containing only 4~positive samples (see
Section~\ref{sec:onset-counts}).  Section~\ref{sec:lopo} re-evaluates
the two strongest configurations under leave-one-patient-out
cross-validation across all 18~patients and a patient-level permutation
null: the headline RF \rocauc{} of $0.879$ collapses to a pooled
LOPO~\rocauc{} of $0.354$ ($p=0.40$) and the headline XGB-inhaler
\rocauc{} of $0.964$ collapses to a pooled LOPO~\rocauc{} of $0.619$
($p=0.22$).  \emph{Neither configuration produces statistically
distinguishable signal under a cross-patient null}; the numbers below
are the right-tail result of a 4-patient draw and should be read in
that light.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Pre-Onset Anticipation -- final-test results on 4~patients.
Tuned-threshold metrics use the train-only-derived
$\tau^{\star}$; 95\% CIs are bootstrap with 2000~resamples.}
\label{tab:onset-headline}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lccccccc}
\toprule
\textbf{Config} & $T$ & $L$ & $W$ & \textbf{\rocauc{}} & \textbf{\prauc{}} &
$F_1^{\,\tau^{\star}}$ & \textbf{Brier} \\
\midrule
RF -- all sensors           & 4 & 14 & 7  & 0.879 [0.80, 1.00] & 0.327 & 0.00 & 0.027 \\
XGB -- all sensors          & 4 & 14 & 0  & 0.759              & 0.269 & 0.40 & 0.019 \\
XGB -- smartinhaler only    & 4 & 14 & 14 & \textbf{0.964}     & \textbf{0.164} & \textbf{0.136} & 0.168 \\
RNN -- (multi-seed, see Tab.~\ref{tab:rnn-multiseed}) & 3 & 14 & 14 & $0.648 \pm 0.263$ & --- & --- & --- \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Three observations are important before reading these numbers, all of
which are conditional on the 4-patient / 4-positive test fold described
in Section~\ref{sec:onset-counts} and reframed by the Phase-V analysis
in Section~\ref{sec:lopo}.  First, the Random-Forest \emph{tuned}~$F_1$
is $0$~at the default $0.5$~cutoff because the model ranks the four
test positives correctly but never crosses the cutoff -- consistent
with a strong-ranking but uncalibrated decision boundary on a
4-positive test set.  Second, the XGBoost smartinhaler-only entry has
the highest \rocauc{} of any configuration we ran; its \prauc{} of
$0.16$ is roughly $20\times$ the prevalence baseline, but this is
before the Phase-V cross-patient evaluation, which is where the
generalisation claim must be tested.  Third, the RNN's $0.648\pm 0.263$
across 5~seeds means the corresponding single-seed report ($0.90$ in
Phase~I conventions) is unsafe; this is the same recurrent-model
fragility documented in Section~\ref{sec:tier3-results}.

\subsection{Caveat: scores cannot be compared to Phase~I}

The Pre-Onset Anticipation numbers in Table~\ref{tab:onset-headline}
share a dataset with Phase~I (Table~\ref{tab:phase1}) but \emph{not} a
task, label, sample population, or test cohort.  Phase~I asks "is this
24-hour window inside a positive week?"; Phase~III asks "does this
patient's $L$-day record precede an episode onset?"  Direct numerical
comparison between the two is methodologically inappropriate, and we
do not perform it.

% ==========================================================================
\section{Phase~V: Generalisation Stress-Test
(Leave-One-Patient-Out and Patient-Level Permutation)}\label{sec:lopo}
% ==========================================================================

The 4-patient test fold in Section~\ref{sec:onset} is what the literature
typically calls "held-out" but is small enough that a single favourable
draw can drive the headline.  To distinguish a real signal from a
4-patient lottery we re-evaluate the two strongest tabular
configurations under leave-one-patient-out cross-validation and a
patient-level permutation null.

\subsection{Protocol}

\paragraph{Leave-one-patient-out (LOPO).}
For each of the 18~patients $p$, train the locked configuration on the
other 17~and predict on $p$.  Compute per-patient
$\rocauc{}_{p}$ and $\prauc{}_{p}$, then pool predictions across folds
and compute a global \rocauc{}/\prauc{}.  No new HPO is run; the locked
configurations are exactly the Phase-III winners.

\paragraph{Patient-level permutation null.}
For each of $K=200$ permutations $\sigma$ of the 18~user keys, replace
each patient's label sequence with another patient's label block,
matched positionally, then re-run the full LOPO.  This breaks the
feature$\,\to\,$label link \emph{at the patient level} while
preserving within-patient temporal structure and per-block positive
prevalence.  The $p$-value is the share of permuted pooled \rocauc{}
values that match or exceed the real pooled \rocauc{}, with the
standard $+1$ smoother.

\subsection{Locked configurations validated}

\begin{enumerate}[nosep,leftmargin=*]
  \item \textbf{RF -- all sensors, $T=4,\,L=14,\,W=7$}\\
        \texttt{class\_weight=balanced, n\_estimators=200,
        max\_depth=None, min\_samples\_leaf=1}.  This is the headline
        all-sensor Random Forest from Table~\ref{tab:onset-headline}.
  \item \textbf{XGB -- smartinhaler only, $T=4,\,L=14,\,W=14$}\\
        \texttt{n\_estimators=200, max\_depth=3, learning\_rate=0.1,
        subsample=1.0, scale\_pos\_weight=auto}.  This is the strongest
        \rocauc{} of the entire sensor-ablation grid.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Results}

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{LOPO and patient-permutation results across all 18~patients.
"Pooled \rocauc{}" concatenates predictions across folds before
computing the metric.  Permutation null is $K=200$ patient-block
shuffles.}
\label{tab:lopo}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lcccc}
\toprule
\textbf{Config} & \textbf{Headline (4-pt test)} &
\textbf{Pooled \rocauc{} (LOPO)} & \textbf{Per-patient \rocauc{}} &
\textbf{$p$-value} \\
\midrule
RF -- all sensors        & 0.879 & \textbf{0.354} &
$0.641 \pm 0.255$ (range $[0.24,1.00]$) & \textbf{0.40} \\
XGB -- smartinhaler only & 0.964 & \textbf{0.619} &
$0.521 \pm 0.293$ & \textbf{0.22} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Patient-permutation null distribution at $K=200$ for each
locked configuration.  Real pooled \rocauc{} should be compared against
the null distribution percentiles in the same row.}
\label{tab:lopo-null}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lcccccc}
\toprule
\textbf{Config} & \textbf{Real} & \textbf{Null mean} &
\textbf{Null std} & \textbf{Null $q_{05}$} & \textbf{Null $q_{95}$} &
\textbf{$p$-value} \\
\midrule
RF -- all sensors        & 0.354 & 0.342 & 0.165 & 0.125 & 0.664 & 0.40 \\
XGB -- smartinhaler only & 0.619 & 0.440 & 0.209 & 0.135 & 0.807 & 0.22 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Interpretation}\label{sec:lopo-interp}

\paragraph{The headline RF (\rocauc{} = 0.879) does not generalise.}
Pooled LOPO \rocauc{} is $0.354$, worse than chance, and lies almost
exactly at the patient-permutation null mean ($0.342$).  The
permutation $p$-value of $0.40$ means the observed performance is
statistically indistinguishable from a model trained on
patient-permuted labels.  The Phase~IV headline reflects a favourable
draw of four test patients whose ranking pattern happens to match what
the model learned from the other thirteen; that pattern does not
transfer to the cohort as a whole.

\paragraph{The inhaler-only XGB also fails to reject the null.}
Pooled LOPO \rocauc{} is $0.619$ -- about $0.86\,\sigma$ above the
permutation null mean -- with $p=0.22$.  We explicitly do \emph{not}
read this as ``directional evidence'' of a real effect: $p=0.22$ is
far from significant at any standard threshold, the real value sits
comfortably inside the $[q_{05},\,q_{95}]$ envelope of the null
($[0.135,\,0.807]$ in Table~\ref{tab:lopo-null}), and a non-trivial
fraction of the null distribution exceeds the observed performance.
The honest statement is: \emph{we cannot reject the null hypothesis;
the observed performance is consistent with random patient-label
matching}.  No tabular configuration we evaluated produces statistical
evidence of cross-patient generalisation at $\alpha=0.05$.

\paragraph{Per-patient dispersion and a coverage-aware check.}
The per-patient \rocauc{} standard deviation of $0.26$--$0.29$ in
Table~\ref{tab:lopo}, combined with the recurrent-model seed standard
deviation of $0.26$ in Table~\ref{tab:rnn-multiseed}, says the same
thing twice: at this cohort size, any single number reported on any
single split is dominated by which patients happen to be on which side
of the split rather than by the underlying signal.

Because per-patient HR-missingness ranges from $18.06\%$ to $61.57\%$
(Section~\ref{sec:data}), a natural concern is that the LOPO collapse
is driven by patients with very sparse sensor coverage in their
pre-onset windows rather than by absence of cross-patient signal.  We
therefore stratified the per-patient RF-all-sensors LOPO
\rocauc{}s in Table~\ref{tab:lopo} by the HR-missingness tier of the
held-out patient (excluding 9 folds with no test positives or no
test negatives, for which \rocauc{} is undefined):

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{RF -- all-sensors per-patient LOPO \rocauc{} stratified by
the held-out patient's HR missingness, restricted to the 9 folds with
defined \rocauc{}.  The relationship is non-monotone and, if anything,
runs opposite to the coverage hypothesis on this cohort.}
\label{tab:lopo-coverage}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
\textbf{HR-missingness tier} & \textbf{Held-out patients} & \textbf{Mean per-patient \rocauc{}} \\
\midrule
Low ($<\!25\%$)             & 113, 294, 343, 447, 701, 939 & 0.555 \\
Mid ($25$--$40\%$)           & 625                          & 1.000 \\
High ($>\!40\%$)             & 473, 808                     & 0.720 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

High-missingness patients score \emph{higher}, not lower, in this
check; the LOPO collapse is therefore not parsimoniously explained as
a sensor-coverage artefact on this cohort.  The stratified result is
itself fragile -- the high-missingness tier contains only two patients
with defined \rocauc{} -- but it is the available evidence and is
consistent with the interpretation that the underlying obstacle is
cross-patient signal generalisation, not within-patient signal
attenuation.  A larger cohort with a stratified LOPO across
missingness, age band, and severity tier remains the most informative
next experiment.

% ==========================================================================
\section{Discussion}\label{sec:discussion}
% ==========================================================================

\subsection{What this work establishes}

Three results are robust to the methodological audit:

\begin{enumerate}[nosep]
  \item \textbf{The reformulated task is the correct one.}  Anchoring
        positives on the day before each clinical onset removes the
        weekly-label propagation problem of Phase~I and produces a
        sample population that matches the clinical question.  The
        Phase~III leakage probe (mean permuted \rocauc{}~=~0.5046)
        confirms that no inadvertent label-side leakage survives the
        new sample construction.
  \item \textbf{Sensor selection is the most plausible candidate signal.}
        Smartinhaler-only features produce the highest \rocauc{} of any
        configuration in the grid on the favourable test fold and the
        highest pooled LOPO~\rocauc{} ($0.62$ vs.\ $0.35$ for the
        all-sensor RF), but the patient-permutation test does not
        reject the null for any modality subset ($p=0.22$).  Smartwatch
        data are useful but not sufficient on this cohort, and at
        $n=18$ even inhaler-only features do not produce statistically
        distinguishable cross-patient performance.
  \item \textbf{Reporting protocol matters more than architecture
        choice.}  The progress-report headline of $0.717$ for the GRU
        is reproducible in the reformulated pipeline -- but only on a
        favourable 4-patient draw and only for a favourable random
        seed.  The single-number reporting convention used in much of
        the wearable-asthma literature is, on this cohort, not
        meaningful.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{What this work does \emph{not} establish}

\begin{enumerate}[nosep]
  \item \textbf{Cross-patient generalisation.}  No tabular or
        deep-learning configuration in this report achieves a
        cross-patient effect size that survives the patient-permutation
        null at $\alpha=0.05$.
  \item \textbf{Clinical operating-point selection.}  The
        $F_1$-tuned thresholds from Section~\ref{sec:onset-results} are
        train-only-derived but were not stability-tested across
        patient folds.  Any deployment-style operating point would
        require a much larger cohort.
  \item \textbf{Modality-specific causal claims.}  Although
        smartinhaler features dominate the ablation,
        18~patients is too small to attribute the effect to any
        specific behavioural mechanism rather than to dataset-level
        coincidence between rescue-inhaler use timing and questionnaire
        completion.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Implications for similar cohorts}

The pattern observed here -- 5-seed test \rocauc{} of $0.65~\pm~0.26$ and
LOPO pooled \rocauc{} of $0.35$--$0.62$ -- is a quantitative version of
a problem that the wearable-asthma literature already
notes~\cite{molfino2024,dehond2022,cokorudy2024} but does not always
control for.  A few practical recommendations follow:

\begin{itemize}[nosep]
  \item Patient-disjoint splits are necessary but not sufficient;
        when $n_{\text{test}}\leq 5$, the headline number should
        always be accompanied by an LOPO companion.
  \item For recurrent models on cohorts of this size, single-seed
        results are not interpretable.  At least 5 seeds and an
        explicit standard deviation should be reported as a matter of
        course.
  \item A patient-block permutation null is much more diagnostic than a
        row-level feature shuffle, which can be fooled by per-patient
        confounding (as illustrated by the gap between our
        $0.5046$~row-shuffle ceiling and the $0.40$~patient-permutation
        $p$-value for the RF).
\end{itemize}

% ==========================================================================
\section{Limitations}\label{sec:limits}
% ==========================================================================

\paragraph{Cohort size.}
The binding limitation throughout this report is $n=18$ usable patients.
Even a perfectly clean experimental protocol cannot produce significant
generalisation evidence at this scale when the per-patient
within-class variance is comparable to the between-class effect.

\paragraph{Single-study cohort.}
AAMOS-00 is a single UK-based study with a particular age, severity,
and adherence profile.  Models trained here would require external
validation on at least one independent multimodal cohort before any
deployment-style claim.

\paragraph{Coarse questionnaire ground truth.}
The weekly worsening score is the only available proxy for
exacerbation onset.  It is more reliable than self-reported daily
symptoms but coarser than clinically documented events.  Some of the
per-patient \rocauc{} variance in Section~\ref{sec:lopo} is likely
attributable to questionnaire-completion behaviour rather than to
physiological signal.

\paragraph{No physician-grade ground truth on test side.}
The four test patients have 2--5 positives each.  Even a perfect model
on physiological grounds would inherit noise from how those few
positives happen to align with the patient's smartwatch wear pattern,
inhaler reporting, and peak-flow compliance during that specific week.

\paragraph{No cross-patient evaluation for deep-learning families.}
The LOPO and patient-permutation protocol in Section~\ref{sec:lopo}
was applied only to the two strongest tabular configurations.  The
Phase-III multi-seed evidence (Table~\ref{tab:rnn-multiseed}) shows
that the recurrent-model headline is unsafe to interpret as a
single-seed number, but a 5-seed sweep on a fixed 4-patient test fold
is \emph{not} a generalisation test.  An 18-fold $\times$~5-seed LOPO
of the RNN, LSTM, GRU, and CNN families would be needed to claim or
reject cross-patient transfer for the deep-learning side, and we did
not run it.  Consequently, the generalisation of recurrent models
remains untested on this cohort, and the seed-variance argument should
be read as evidence about \emph{reporting stability}, not about
\emph{cross-patient performance}.

\paragraph{No deployment-grade calibration.}
We report Brier scores but do not perform Platt or isotonic
recalibration, both because the test set is too small for stable
calibration learning and because the LOPO instability of the underlying
predictors would propagate directly into any post-hoc calibration map.

% ==========================================================================
\section{Conclusion and Future Work}\label{sec:conclusion}
% ==========================================================================

This report tells the full arc of our project: a smartwatch-only
day-level baseline (Phase~I); a methodological audit that identified
three issues in that baseline (Phase~II); two further deep-learning
families and a multi-seed evaluation protocol (Phase~III); a
clinically reformulated task -- \emph{Event-Episode Pre-Onset
Anticipation} -- with patient-disjoint splits, a 27-cell grid, sensor
ablation, and a label-leakage probe (Phase~IV); and a
generalisation stress-test that re-evaluates the two strongest
configurations under leave-one-patient-out cross-validation and a
patient-level permutation null (Phase~V).

The honest finding is that on $n=18$ patients no configuration we
evaluated -- tabular or sequence -- demonstrates statistically
significant cross-patient generalisation.  Pooled LOPO~\rocauc{} values
of $0.354$ ($p=0.40$) for the all-sensor Random Forest and $0.619$
($p=0.22$) for the smartinhaler-only XGBoost are both consistent with
random patient-label matching.  There is no statistical evidence in
this study to support a deployment-style generalisation claim for any
model.  The headline 4-patient \rocauc{} values that emerge from a
single patient-disjoint split ($0.879$ for RF, $0.964$ for
XGB-inhaler) are computationally correct on that specific test fold
but should not be read as performance estimates.

\subsection{Future work}

\begin{enumerate}[nosep]
  \item \textbf{Larger multimodal cohort.}  The single most consequential
        next step is replicating the Pre-Onset Anticipation pipeline on
        a cohort with $n\geq 50$ patients where the
        patient-permutation null can plausibly be rejected at
        $\alpha=0.05$ for a clinically meaningful effect size.
  \item \textbf{Inhaler-centric modelling.}  The highest pooled LOPO
        \rocauc{} on smartinhaler features, although not significant at
        $n=18$, motivates a focused study with deliberately denser
        inhaler instrumentation, including time-since-last-use kernels
        and circadian decompositions.
  \item \textbf{Personalised per-patient baselines.}  Treating each
        patient's stable-week distribution as an individual reference
        and predicting departures from it -- rather than predicting on
        a population-level decision boundary -- is the natural response
        to the per-patient dispersion documented in
        Table~\ref{tab:lopo}.
  \item \textbf{Multi-horizon evaluation.}  The current task uses a
        single $L$-day pre-onset window.  Extending to overlapping
        $\{3,\,7,\,14\}$-day horizons with shared backbone weights
        would let a clinical operator pick a horizon at deployment
        time rather than at training time.
  \item \textbf{Pretraining on adjacent wearable cohorts.}  Self-supervised
        pretraining on larger generic-wearable corpora (e.g.\ UK Biobank
        smartwatch substudies) before fine-tuning on AAMOS-00 is a
        plausible path to reducing the seed-level variance documented
        in Table~\ref{tab:rnn-multiseed}.
\end{enumerate}

